<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Editorial Team</h1>
  <p>latepaycalc.com is written and reviewed by a small editorial team at The Click Lab. Every element of the late-pay penalty framework is verified against state labor codes, the published guidance of state wage enforcement agencies (California Division of Labor Standards Enforcement, New York DOL, Massachusetts AGO Fair Labor Division, Texas Workforce Commission, and others), and the leading state appellate decisions interpreting final-paycheck and waiting-time-penalty statutes.</p>

  <h2>How we work</h2>
  <p>Every piece of content on this site goes through the same workflow: a contributor drafts the article using primary legal sources (state statutes, state appellate opinions, agency guidance), the editor-in-chief reviews the draft for accuracy and citation quality, the calculator team verifies any formulas or worked examples against current state-law principles, and the final piece is published with the reviewer's byline. Substantive updates are dated; minor typographic corrections are not.</p>
  <p>We don't publish "thin" content. Every guide aims to answer a real question a non-lawyer worker, manager, or HR practitioner might ask &mdash; when must my final paycheck arrive, how do California waiting time penalties actually work, what counts as "wages owed" at separation, what to do when a former employer disputes the amount &mdash; with enough specificity to be useful, while staying honest about the limits of general informational content.</p>

  <h2>Our editorial team</h2>
  <p>Our editorial team draws on senior HR and paralegal experience in wage-and-hour compliance, primarily on the employer side &mdash; designing payroll separation processes, handling final paychecks across multi-state workforces, and resolving wage-claim disputes before they escalate &mdash; as well as supporting wage-claim attorneys on cases involving final-paycheck disputes across multiple states. State final-paycheck rules vary substantially: California requires same-day payment at involuntary termination, Texas allows up to the next regular pay date, New York has separate rules for blue-collar vs. white-collar workers, and several states have no statutory deadline at all. The team writes the methodology, step-by-step penalty-calculation content, and per-state reference guides on this site, citing state wage statutes, state DOL guidance, and the published appellate decisions on waiting time penalties (especially the California case law, which is voluminous) throughout. No team member is a licensed attorney; the work here is informational only.</p>

  <h2>Editorial standards</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cite the authority.</strong> Every rule we discuss is grounded in a specific state statute, agency publication, or appellate decision. When we describe a state's approach, we name the controlling statute and link to it where a free version is available.</li>
    <li><strong>No legal advice.</strong> Everything on this site is general and informational. Specific late-pay disputes need a licensed attorney. We don't review individual paystubs and we don't predict outcomes in particular cases.</li>
    <li><strong>No paid placements in editorial content.</strong> We don't accept money, gifts, or other consideration to recommend products, law firms, or HR-tech tools in our guides or methodology &mdash; no attorney pays for coverage or a favorable mention. The only ads on the site are programmatic Google AdSense ads; we don't choose what runs. Separately, the case-review form on our homepage is a disclosed paid referral: submitting it shares your information with attorneys who may compensate The Click Lab Agency LLC for the introduction. See our <a href="/privacy/">privacy policy</a> for details.</li>
    <li><strong>Plain-language first.</strong> Wage-and-hour terms (<em>waiting time penalty</em>, <em>final paycheck</em>, <em>liquidated damages</em>, <em>itemized wage statement</em>) are defined where we use them. We assume our reader is sharp, but not necessarily formally trained in wage law.</li>
    <li><strong>Worked examples wherever helpful.</strong> Abstract regulatory text without numbers and facts to anchor it is hard to use. Almost every guide includes at least one worked example.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Sources we rely on</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>State labor codes</strong> &mdash; California Labor Code (especially &sect;&sect; 201&ndash;204 and 203), New York Labor Law, Massachusetts wage statutes, Texas Payday Act, and similar primary sources from each state.</li>
    <li><strong>State enforcement-agency guidance</strong> &mdash; DLSE Manual (California), NY DOL fact sheets and opinion letters, Massachusetts AGO Fair Labor Division materials, Texas Workforce Commission publications.</li>
    <li><strong>State appellate decisions</strong> &mdash; leading cases interpreting final-paycheck and waiting-time-penalty statutes, especially California (where the case law is voluminous).</li>
    <li><strong>Federal FLSA</strong> &mdash; while final-paycheck rules are primarily state-law, the federal FLSA's prompt-payment principle and the related back-wages framework apply when state law doesn't.</li>
    <li><strong>Court opinions</strong> &mdash; cited via free databases (CourtListener, Google Scholar) where opinions are publicly reachable.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Corrections</h2>
  <p>If you find an error &mdash; a wrong statutory citation, a state-law summary that's outdated, a calculator output that doesn't match the underlying formula &mdash; please email <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a> with the page URL and what's wrong. Verified corrections are typically made within a few business days. Material corrections are noted at the bottom of the affected page with the date of the change.</p>

  <h2>Reviewer disclosures</h2>
  <p>Our contributors are not licensed attorneys and do not practice law. They are HR-compliance and paralegal professionals with substantive experience in wage-and-hour matters. Reviewing employment-law content for accuracy is part of an HR-compliance practitioner's and paralegal's professional skill set and is not the same as giving legal advice. Nothing on this site should be construed as legal advice, and nothing here creates an attorney-client relationship with any contributor or with The Click Lab.</p>

  <h2>Contact the editorial team</h2>
  <p>Editorial questions, citation suggestions, or interview requests: <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. We respond within a few business days.</p>
</BaseLayout>
